Protect International Material; Deter, detect and interdict illicit trafficking in nuclear/radioactive materials.

The Office of Radiological Security (ORS) plays an important role in preventing radiological terrorism at home and abroad by working with partners to secure radioactive materials that could be used in acts of terrorism. Radioactive materials, especially those in the form of radioactive sources, are used worldwide to diagnose and treat diseases such as cancer, to sterilize medical instruments and food, and to monitor the structural integrity of materials and industrial processes. These same radioactive sources, if not adequately protected, pose a risk to the safety and security of our Nation and the international community.

The funding supports U.S. experts to serve as Working Group B (WGB) Task Leaders and Expert Group Chair during biannual Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty (CTBT) WGB technical meetings in Vienna, Austria focused on international nuclear explosion monitoring issues.

The award funds U.S. National Laboratories to prepare for and execute international nuclear safeguards engagement activities, including training, consultations, and technical collaboration with foreign nuclear regulatory agencies, nuclear operator agencies, and related organizations.

The U.S. Department of Energy's National Nuclear Security Administration (DOE/NNSA) Office of International Nuclear Security (INS) works to lead and partner in U.S. international efforts to prevent threat and sabotage of nuclear materials and facilities worldwide by strengthening global nuclear security norms through White House initiatives on cybersecurity, insider threat mitigation, and transport security.

Export Control Outreach. The International Nonproliferation Export Control Program (INECP) bolsters domestic and international capacity to counter illicit acquisition of WMD-related dual use commodities by strengthening strategic trade and export control systems.

The Department of Energy National Nuclear Security Administration (DOE/NNSA) Office of Nuclear Smuggling Detection and Deterrence (NSDD) works with international partners to strengthen capabilities to deter, detect, and investigate the smuggling of nuclear and radiological materials by providing the expertise and tools needed to respond to smuggling events.
